    "headline": "Residents Throw Away a Third Less Waste Than 15 Years Ago",
    "lede": "Most households set out their bins every week, but the numbers reveal something surprising: we’re now tossing out much less than before. In Reykjavík, the amount of household waste per person has dropped by about a third since 1998—falling from 266 kilos a year to just 173 kilos by 2012.",
    "story_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "callout",
        "body": "Each person in Reykjavík is now throwing away about a third less than they did 15 years ago.",
        "highlight_value": "35% less",
        "highlight_label": "waste per person since 1998"
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Waste Per Person Drops After Peaking in 2000",
        "body": "In the chart below, you'll see how waste collected per person crept up to a high of 273 kilos around the year 2000. After that, there’s a steady and sharp decline right through to 2012. By the end of this period, the average resident is producing 37% less waste than at the peak. This is the most dramatic shift in the numbers.",
        "viz_index": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Number of Collection Bins Also Decreases",
        "body": "Look next at the chart showing how many waste bins the city had to empty each year. The number of bins went up until 2004, reaching a high point, but then fell by about a fifth over the next eight years. By 2012, crews were collecting from nearly 11,000 fewer bins than at the peak. This fall matches the drop in waste per person and shows a real change in how much is being thrown away.",
        "viz_index": 0
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "What This Means for Residents",
        "body": "Filling your bin less means less waste picked up, fewer trips for city trucks, and likely lower costs for everyone. Seeing our habits shift so much in just over a decade hints at big changes in what—and how much—we use and throw away. For households, it means we’re all playing a part in making Reykjavík a bit cleaner and less wasteful."
      }
    ],
    "data_note": "This story covers waste collection in Reykjavík households from 1998 to 2012. All numbers are citywide averages—your home's habits may differ. The figures come from the city's Environment and Planning division, but licence details are not specified, and costs after 2012 aren't included. Finally, big changes in 2004 and 2005 may be due to policy shifts, so keep in mind that the trends shown reflect both resident behavior and city practices.",
    "followup_question": "How is public transport ridership trending?",
